This problem asks me to implement variable-length integer (varint) encoding and decoding using the Hexi library. Let me think about how varint encoding typically works:

1. Varint encoding uses the most significant bit (MSB) of each byte as a continuation bit:
   - If MSB is 1, there are more bytes to follow
   - If MSB is 0, this is the last byte
   - The remaining 7 bits store the actual data

2. For encoding:
   - Take the lower 7 bits of the value
   - If there are more significant bits, set the MSB to 1
   - Shift the value right by 7 bits
   - Repeat until the value is 0

3. For decoding:
   - Read a byte
   - Take the lower 7 bits and add to result
   - If MSB is 1, shift result left by 7 and continue
   - If MSB is 0, we're done

Looking at the Hexi library usage, it seems we have:
- `hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer` for writing bytes
- `hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader` for reading bytes

Let me implement these functions:

```cpp
#include <hexi/shared.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_writer.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_reader.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

using namespace hexi::detail;

template<typename T>
std::size_t encode_varint(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, T value) {
    std::size_t bytes_written = 0;

    // Handle the value as unsigned to avoid issues with sign extension
    using UnsignedT = typename std::make_unsigned<T>::type;
    UnsignedT uvalue = static_cast<UnsignedT>(value);

    do {
        uint8_t byte = uvalue & 0x7F;  // Take lower 7 bits
        uvalue >>= 7;  // Shift right by 7 bits

        if (uvalue != 0) {
            byte |= 0x80;  // Set MSB if more bytes follow
        }

        writer.write(byte);
        bytes_written++;
    } while (uvalue != 0);

